In this document I play around with the DHARMa package, using some code snippets from the package tutorial as well as adding some of my own.

Example of “good” model

Here in the simulated data the outcome is generated from a Poisson distribution. We fit a GLM with logit link function and use DHARMa to evaluate the results- which do not indicate anything troubling with the model.

#install.packages("DHARMa")
library(DHARMa)
library(lme4)
library(gtsummary)
library(MASS)
library(tidyverse)

set.seed(1219)
testData = createData(sampleSize = 250)

Let’s peak at the simulated data:

hist(testData$Environment1)

hist(testData$observedResponse)

testData %>%
  select(observedResponse, Environment1, group) %>%
  tbl_summary(by = group)
Characteristic 1, N = 251 2, N = 251 3, N = 251 4, N = 251 5, N = 251 6, N = 251 7, N = 251 8, N = 251 9, N = 251 10, N = 251
observedResponse 0 (0, 0) 0 (0, 1) 2 (0, 3) 3 (1, 5) 2 (1, 4) 4 (2, 6) 0 (0, 1) 1 (0, 1) 0 (0, 1) 0 (0, 0)
Environment1 -0.06 (-0.43, 0.62) -0.11 (-0.51, 0.54) -0.38 (-0.58, 0.02) 0.23 (-0.32, 0.57) 0.07 (-0.53, 0.48) -0.12 (-0.60, 0.28) -0.22 (-0.40, 0.20) 0.15 (-0.32, 0.62) 0.28 (-0.35, 0.56) -0.29 (-0.53, 0.17)
1 Median (IQR) 
fittedModel <- glmer(observedResponse ~ Environment1 + (1|group) , 
                     family = "poisson", data = testData)

testDispersion(fittedModel)

## 
##  DHARMa nonparametric dispersion test via sd of residuals fitted vs.
##  simulated
## 
## data:  simulationOutput
## dispersion = 0.43047, p-value = 0.96
## alternative hypothesis: two.sided
simulationOutput <- simulateResiduals(fittedModel = fittedModel)

plot(simulationOutput)

plotResiduals(simulationOutput, form = testData$group)

testDispersion(simulationOutput)

## 
##  DHARMa nonparametric dispersion test via sd of residuals fitted vs.
##  simulated
## 
## data:  simulationOutput
## dispersion = 0.43047, p-value = 0.96
## alternative hypothesis: two.sided

Example of overdispersion

Next we generate simulated data with overdispersion. When we fit a poisson model to this data and use the DHARMa functions lots of red flags come up.

testData2 = createData(sampleSize = 200, overdispersion = 1.5, family = poisson())
fittedModel2 <- glm(observedResponse ~  Environment1 , family = "poisson", data = testData2)

Let’s peak at the simulated data:

hist(testData2$Environment1)

hist(testData2$observedResponse)

testData2 %>%
  select(observedResponse, Environment1, group) %>%
  tbl_summary(by = group)
Characteristic 1, N = 201 2, N = 201 3, N = 201 4, N = 201 5, N = 201 6, N = 201 7, N = 201 8, N = 201 9, N = 201 10, N = 201
observedResponse 0 (0, 1) 2 (1, 10) 2 (0, 4) 0 (0, 0) 0 (0, 4) 1 (0, 2) 1 (0, 2) 5 (1, 8) 2 (0, 9) 2 (1, 10)
Environment1 -0.02 (-0.31, 0.27) 0.00 (-0.31, 0.28) 0.14 (-0.37, 0.71) -0.41 (-0.54, 0.20) 0.19 (-0.32, 0.57) 0.09 (-0.66, 0.40) -0.18 (-0.54, 0.36) -0.51 (-0.77, -0.01) -0.08 (-0.40, 0.17) 0.08 (-0.43, 0.30)

simulationOutput2 <- simulateResiduals(fittedModel = fittedModel2)
plot(simulationOutput2)

testDispersion(simulationOutput2)

## 
##  DHARMa nonparametric dispersion test via sd of residuals fitted vs.
##  simulated
## 
## data:  simulationOutput
## dispersion = 45.256, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: two.sided

Finally I fit a negative binomial model to that overdispersed data, simulated new output and tested the results using DHARMa. Now it does not detect significant deviations!

fittedModel_negbin<- glm.nb(observedResponse ~  Environment1 , data = testData2)
simulationOutput3 <- simulateResiduals(fittedModel = fittedModel_negbin)
plot(simulationOutput3)

testDispersion(simulationOutput3)

## 
##  DHARMa nonparametric dispersion test via sd of residuals fitted vs.
##  simulated
## 
## data:  simulationOutput
## dispersion = 1.403, p-value = 0.312
## alternative hypothesis: two.sided
